WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.680
Hello, I'm Carl, I work on the IDE team here at RStudio, and today I'm going to be talking

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:15.440
about how to use Jupyter with RStudio Server Pro.

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:18.360
So I'm going to talk about, you know, why would you want to do this, how do you set

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:24.680
it up, how do you administer it, and I'll show you a brief little demo of it.

00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:28.240
So to start, some of you may be wondering, why are we doing this?

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:33.840
So you know, R isn't going anywhere, we very strongly believe in R, but as a company we're

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:40.279
very much invested in making the R ecosystem as great as it can be, and at the same time

00:00:40.279 --> 00:00:44.020
we're committed to supporting the open source data science ecosystem as a whole, regardless

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:45.619
of language choice.

00:00:45.619 --> 00:00:50.320
So you know, that said, R and Python are not rivals, they're both great tools for data

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:55.599
science and we believe strongly in both of them, and you know, R's better for some things

00:00:55.599 --> 00:00:59.720
than others, and Python's better for other things.

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:04.000
So you know, combining them will provide us the best of both worlds and give everyone

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.239
what they need to do their data science effectively.

00:01:08.239 --> 00:01:13.839
So you know, I barely scratch the surface on, you know, our aim as a company to, you

00:01:13.839 --> 00:01:17.639
know, kind of combine Python and R and, you know, provide you the best tools that you

00:01:17.639 --> 00:01:23.699
need to do your job, but on our website we have an R and Python love story that I highly

00:01:23.699 --> 00:01:28.019
recommend you to read, it's very good and goes into more depth about, you know, where

00:01:28.019 --> 00:01:29.660
we're going as a company.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:32.540
You can read that on rstudio.com.

00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:36.019
So why use Jupyter specifically?

00:01:36.019 --> 00:01:39.900
Jupyter is well known in the Python community, and it provides a lot of tooling for working

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:42.739
with various versions of Python seamlessly.

00:01:42.739 --> 00:01:49.699
It also provides Jupyter notebooks, which many of you may know are great ways of organizing

00:01:49.699 --> 00:01:54.860
and visualizing data, similar to our markdown documents, but currently provide better Python

00:01:54.860 --> 00:02:00.139
integration.

00:02:00.139 --> 00:02:04.139
So why would you want to use Jupyter from RStudio Server Pro?

00:02:04.139 --> 00:02:09.460
So doing so allows you to provide a one-stop portal for all of your data science needs.

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:15.820
So there's no need to manage multiple portals and frameworks for your users to log in and

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:17.580
just to do their jobs.

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:21.979
You also get all the auth and authorization benefits that you get from RStudio sessions

00:02:21.979 --> 00:02:27.979
with Jupyter now, and that's a huge boon for administrators.

00:02:27.979 --> 00:02:29.940
It's also a better user experience.

00:02:29.940 --> 00:02:35.820
So right now if you want your data scientists to use Jupyter, you have to have them connect

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:40.339
to it via a terminal, start it through the terminal, and, you know, that's just not a

00:02:40.339 --> 00:02:41.460
great user experience.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:46.100
So, you know, integrating it in with RStudio Server Pro allows them to, you know, launch

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:52.139
it just like an R session and get access to Jupyter at the touch of their fingertips.

00:02:52.139 --> 00:02:56.380
And finally, if you integrate Jupyter with RStudio Server Pro, it becomes very easy to

00:02:56.380 --> 00:03:01.460
publish Jupyter notebooks to connect, which gives you a great sharing ecosystem that we've

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:07.100
built with R but also with Python.

00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:11.460
So I just want to quickly very basic talk about architecture, just so you can kind of

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:14.740
understand how this all works.

00:03:14.740 --> 00:03:21.020
So, you know, today we have RStudio Server Pro and now it talks to the launcher, which

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:22.979
Jonathan talked about in the last talk.

00:03:22.979 --> 00:03:27.779
I won't talk about the launcher in depth here, but basically it allows you to launch your

00:03:27.779 --> 00:03:33.220
R sessions and your Python Jupyter sessions potentially in the cloud via Kubernetes or

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:38.360
Slurm or also locally as well on the local server.

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:42.139
But the key takeaway here is that Jupyter sessions require the use of the launcher,

00:03:42.139 --> 00:03:47.899
which is a new feature in 1.2, and R and Jupyter sessions are peers of each other,

00:03:47.899 --> 00:03:51.100
so they're treated very much the same way.

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:57.300
And I'll kind of explain what that means when I do my demo.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:07.139
So to talk about how to use it, so again, you need the job launcher, so I won't go into

00:04:07.139 --> 00:04:08.619
detail there.

00:04:08.619 --> 00:04:12.259
There's plenty of documentation online that you can find about that.

00:04:12.259 --> 00:04:17.179
But once you have that enabled, all you really have to do to turn on Jupyter sessions is

00:04:17.179 --> 00:04:19.980
to flip some switches and set a binary path.

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:21.480
It's very simple.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:25.940
So a sample configuration file just to enable Jupyter is this.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:31.339
You just set the binary path for Jupyter and then turn on labs, Jupyter labs for the Jupyter

00:04:31.339 --> 00:04:35.640
labs interface or notebooks for the Jupyter notebooks interface, and you can have both

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:38.059
of those at the same time.

00:04:38.059 --> 00:04:46.179
I'm going to attempt to show you a demo here, if I can figure out where my desktop is.

00:04:46.179 --> 00:04:56.179
Okay, so this is the RStudio Server Pro homepage, and some of you may be familiar with this,

00:04:56.179 --> 00:05:04.500
but right now, when we launch a session, what's new is we can choose our editor.

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:09.279
So before, every time you would start a new session, you only had one option, which was

00:05:09.279 --> 00:05:11.440
to launch RStudio.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:17.600
But now, you have the option to start JupyterLab or JupyterNotebook.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:21.200
So just real quick to show you what that might look like, if I start a JupyterLab session,

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:27.519
it shows up on the homepage, and then I'm loaded into JupyterLab very seamlessly.

00:05:27.519 --> 00:05:33.200
And then you can interact with Jupyter just like you would regularly connecting to Jupyter.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:38.579
You have access to multiple documents at the same time, and that sort of thing.

00:05:38.579 --> 00:05:44.299
So nothing revolutionary, but it is great that you can access that through the homepage

00:05:44.299 --> 00:05:48.899
of RStudio Server Pro.

00:05:48.899 --> 00:05:51.500
Now I'll just quickly show you JupyterNotebook.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:56.220
I want to show you how easy it is to publish a JupyterNotebook to Connect.

00:05:56.220 --> 00:06:06.079
So if I started a new JupyterNotebook session, and then let's create a new Python notebook.

00:06:06.079 --> 00:06:13.279
So I'll just print some Python code here.

00:06:13.279 --> 00:06:18.799
And then you'll see that in the JupyterNotebook, it's a little hard to see, let's make it bigger.

00:06:18.799 --> 00:06:22.140
There's this button here that allows us to publish to Connect.

00:06:22.140 --> 00:06:27.239
So if we click that, it becomes very easy to publish it.

00:06:27.239 --> 00:06:35.480
All I have to do is click Publish, and then it shows up on RStudio Connect.

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:39.799
So this is the new notebook that I just created, and then there it is.

00:06:39.799 --> 00:06:50.799
Very simple.

00:06:50.799 --> 00:06:56.980
So I just want to quickly talk about best practices for administering Jupyter with RStudio

00:06:56.980 --> 00:06:59.299
Server Pro.

00:06:59.299 --> 00:07:03.380
I recommend that you use the default configuration wherever possible, because we've put a lot

00:07:03.380 --> 00:07:09.380
of work into making the configuration defaults just work out of the box with very sane defaults

00:07:09.380 --> 00:07:11.799
that you shouldn't need to be tweaking.

00:07:11.799 --> 00:07:18.140
But two settings that you may actually want to tweak are related to session suspension

00:07:18.140 --> 00:07:22.899
and automatically cleaning up sessions that were forgotten about.

00:07:22.899 --> 00:07:31.160
So similar to what we have today for R sessions like suspend, we provide for Jupyter as well.

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:36.200
And then when you're mounting your NFS directory, you need to mount NFS directories so that

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:38.279
users have access to their notebooks.

00:07:38.279 --> 00:07:43.700
And if you're doing that with NFSv3, we recommend using local lock equals all as a mount option

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:45.559
or just using NFSv4.

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:48.359
Otherwise you could run into some problems there.

00:07:48.359 --> 00:07:51.959
And then if you're going to be using this with Kubernetes, we recommend that you use

00:07:51.959 --> 00:07:55.799
the R session complete RStudio Docker image.

00:07:55.799 --> 00:08:00.760
So this is basically a Docker image that we published to Docker Hub that has all the RStudio

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:08.500
binaries that you need to launch Jupyter, and then it has Jupyter itself and an installation

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:13.760
of Python, and then you can create derivative images from that to provide your users with

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:19.760
whatever you need in terms of Python versions.

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:26.760
So there are two plugins that we provide for Jupyter to kind of help with the user experience.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:30.519
These are totally optional, but I recommend that you have both of these installed.

00:08:30.519 --> 00:08:33.979
The first plugin is the RSConnect Jupyter plugin, which is what actually allowed us

00:08:33.979 --> 00:08:37.700
to publish the notebook to Jupyter.

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:42.599
And then the other one is the RSP plugin, which shows notebooks on the homepage.

00:08:42.599 --> 00:08:47.320
So just to remind you what that looks like, at the top you see the connect publishing

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:53.239
button, and then at the bottom on the homepage you'll see your recently used notebooks on

00:08:53.239 --> 00:08:57.760
the homepage as well.

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:02.599
So in some rare cases, you know, Jupyter won't start right up out of the box.

00:09:02.599 --> 00:09:06.640
We've tried to make it as easy as possible, but there may come a time where, you know,

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:09.840
you see that your Jupyter sessions won't start for whatever reason.

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:12.659
So if you need help troubleshooting those issues, the first thing I would recommend

00:09:12.659 --> 00:09:18.059
to do is run the verify installation command, and this is documented in the RStudio Server

00:09:18.059 --> 00:09:19.940
Pro admin guide.

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:21.359
It's very easy to use.

00:09:21.359 --> 00:09:26.400
You just run it, and it gives you information about why your job couldn't start.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:29.820
So hopefully you can use that information to fix whatever's going wrong.

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:33.820
And if you need further help, just reach out to support.

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:40.000
As far as next steps go, if you're interested in integrating Jupyter with the RStudio Server

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:48.799
Pro, please go to the website on screen, solutions.rstudio.com, and we have a great primer to help you set

00:09:48.799 --> 00:09:49.799
this up.

00:09:49.799 --> 00:09:50.799
And that's it.

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:51.799
Thank you.

00:09:51.799 --> 00:09:52.799
Thanks, Carl.

00:09:52.799 --> 00:10:03.159
We have a number of different questions that we can go ahead and work through.

00:10:03.159 --> 00:10:07.539
One of the questions was, are all Jupyter kernels supported, Python, R, Julia, et cetera?

00:10:07.539 --> 00:10:09.419
Are those available?

00:10:09.419 --> 00:10:14.020
We've just focused on the Python kernel for now.

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:17.700
The one thing that I will mention is it's just Jupyter, so anything you can do in Jupyter,

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:18.700
you can do here.

00:10:18.700 --> 00:10:19.700
Let's see.

00:10:19.700 --> 00:10:20.700
There's another one.

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:23.419
How does Jupyter handle ODBC connections to databases?

00:10:23.419 --> 00:10:28.359
Is there anything specific to RStudio Server Pro done there?

00:10:28.359 --> 00:10:30.799
There's nothing specific done for ODBC.

00:10:30.799 --> 00:10:37.340
It should just be a complete pass-through for whatever you have set up with Jupyter.

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:38.340
Another question.

00:10:38.340 --> 00:10:43.179
Why not enable Jupyter by default on RStudio 1.3?

00:10:43.179 --> 00:10:53.179
I guess that means, why is it not in the open-source version, or why is it just not enabled?

00:10:53.179 --> 00:10:57.820
Because to enable it, you have to actually have it set up and configured and installed,

00:10:57.820 --> 00:11:04.859
so basically we don't want to forcefully turn that on if it hasn't been set up.

00:11:04.859 --> 00:11:09.619
Are there any tools for admins to be able to kill and manage Jupyter sessions?

00:11:09.619 --> 00:11:14.539
It's really easy to kill Jupyter sessions from the home page, like regular R sessions,

00:11:14.539 --> 00:11:20.179
so users can self-administer that sort of thing, and admins can see Jupyter sessions

00:11:20.179 --> 00:11:24.900
from the RStudio Server Pro admin page, so if they need to kill sessions, they can do

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:27.020
that very easily.

00:11:27.020 --> 00:11:33.940
Will the Jupyter integration be available in the RStudio desktop IDE in the future?

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:34.940
I don't know.

00:11:34.940 --> 00:11:35.940
Maybe, perhaps.

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:36.940
Great.

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:37.940
Thanks again, Karl.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:38.940
All right.

00:11:38.940 --> 00:11:39.940
All right.

00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:39.940


